<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Malosma laurina </i>is a large, large-leaved sclerophyllous shrub that grows to 5 m in height. Shrubs produce low, but consistent crops of fleshy drupes. Birds and small mammals dispersed the seeds. The stones accumulate in duff and soil as a seed bank. Seedlings establish in full sun or shade, but survive better in the shade of established shrubs. Seedlings and leaves are sensitive to frost. The species increases in importance in stands as they age (Howard 1992f). <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is often overlooked by combining it with other chaparral or coastal scrub types. Many characteristic chaparral genera (<i>Adenostoma, Arctostaphylos, Ceanothus, Quercus</i>) are absent or occur only uncommonly (Rundel 2007). Miller and Poole (1979) described water use of sumacs and other shrubs. The abundance and cover of <i>M. laurina </i>increase with decreasing soil moisture water holding capacity and with higher absolute minimum temperatures (Westman 1981b). Stands at the uppermost elevations and inland relate to the plantâ€™s frost sensitivity (Davis et al. 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
