    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Malosma laurina</i> includes the Central California Coast (261A) to San Luis Obispo Co.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb, Bd-j). Stands occur on the mainland in San Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) and throughout most of the section where stands have increased in recent decades (S. Davis, pers. comm. 2003, Taylor 2004). The species is known from the southern Channel Islands and stands have been sampled on Santa Catalina Island (Dixon et al. 2019).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bj, Bn). Stands exist in the Puente Hills (S. White 1994c), in central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005), and in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Schinus molle </i>and <i>S. terebinthifolius </i>are increasingly naturalizing in stands of this alliance. Stands of <i>Malosma laurina </i>in San Diego Co. have been removed to make way for viticulture.  Brush clearing and frequent fire favor <i>M. laurina </i>and herbs in stands historically dominated by <i>Artemisia californica </i>or <i>Salvia leucophylla</i>. 

Between 2012 to 2016, southern California experienced unprecedented drought, which has caused shrub dieback of <i>M. laurina </i>. Dieback has been severe in coastal exposures of the Santa Monica Mountains, leading to plant mortality exceeding 50% at some sites. Dieback appears to be from drought stress coupled with invasion of an endophytic fungus,<i> Botryosphaeria dothidea</i>, which blocks water transport of xylem leading to branch dieback and eventual whole plant mortality (Sauer et al. 2016, Aguirre et al. 2017). </div>
</div>

    

    

